title Ojjo — a palindrome O-vane that proves Hoon/Glow parity by measuring it
prompt Keaton proposed a new O-vane, Ojjo (a palindrome), a TAME-guidance safety/performance benchmarking vane proving parity between Hoon programs scripting Dojo/Arvo and Glow programs scripting Rish/Glow, each system's own timer recording compile+runtime stats so we Measure What Matters. Asked to write a gratitude on the book referencing High Output Management, TAME, and TigerBeetle, expand and run the prompt, and give an honest opinion.
think Checked the name in collision research before endorsing it: no language/OS/kernel named Ojjo — only OjjO Software, the Ojoo low-code platform, and the unrelated Xojo IDE, none in domain. Low collision risk. The palindrome is not decoration: it names the load-bearing discipline of a parity harness — the yardstick must read the same both ways, treating the Hoon side and the Glow side identically, or the benchmark is not fair. O also follows Neth's N and is four letters, so it fits the vane family by shape.
think Held the IP line again: Measure What Matters (Doerr) and High Output Management (Grove) are copyrighted books, so gratitude/MeasureWhatMatters.md is an own-words principles summary like Systemantics/PathWithHeart, per the gratitude-licenses rule — named the elder (Grove) first since OKRs grew from HOM, and carried the transferable core (measure output not activity; name the objective before the metric; few honest transparent measures) while setting down the corporate cadence.
think Designed Ojjo as the project's own values pointed at one real question rather than a new philosophy: correctness parity first (a welcome/unwelcome witness — same input, byte-identical output, or red), performance parity second (compile time + runtime, each side timed by its OWN clock so neither is measured by the other's), steadiness third (best-of-N + variance, TigerBeetle's distribution-beats-a-sample instinct). Every run stamped with the warm-aura date atom as an append-only measurement fact.
think Gave the honest opinion the ask wanted, with real substance rather than flattery: I like it, with two refinements and one caution. Refinement 1 — build correctness-first (lap 1 = conformance suite, no timing at all), timing-second, so the first witness is small and unfakeable and delivers value (proof Glow matches Hoon) before any performance number is trustworthy. Refinement 2 — the timer is a host seam, not a core: wall-clock is noisy and host-dependent, so report the host (GLOW_PROFILE.bron) beside every number and never pin a cross-host performance promise. Caution — Goodhart: a benchmark that becomes a target lies; keep correctness the hard gate and treat fast-but-wrong as the worst outcome, measuring to learn, never to win (the same reason the reframe set down competition-as-engine).
think Named the honest gate plainly: Ojjo has nothing to measure until Glow can run a program, so recommended confirming it now as a named O-vane and building it correctness-first when Glow's first program exists — or deferring entirely as a horizon vane if benchmarking is judged premature. Added it to names-awaiting-confirmation with that now-or-horizon question, wrote the expanding-prompt with the four-lap ladder (conformance -> timing -> steadiness -> task set), and left it design-only: no vane code written.
obs Ojjo is a genuinely good fit because it is not a new idea — it is Two Rooms + Civic Style + TAME (safety before performance) aimed at "is our fused language actually competitive?", a question that otherwise gets answered by feel and quietly drives bad calls. The palindrome name earning its keep as the symmetry discipline is the kind of name-teaches-function the LEXICON prizes.
file gratitude/MeasureWhatMatters.md why: IP-safe summary of Doerr + Grove; grounds Ojjo's measurement discipline
file gratitude/README.md why: gratitude index entry for Measure What Matters
file external-research/20260714-025200_ojjo-benchmarking-vane-design.md why: the full Ojjo design, the four teachers, and the honest opinion with refinements and the Goodhart caution
file expanding-prompts/20260714-025200_ojjo-benchmarking-vane.md why: the correctness-first / timing-second build ladder, gated on Glow running a program
file context/specs/20260713-235600_names-awaiting-confirmation.md why: Ojjo added as the O-vane awaiting confirm, with the now-or-horizon question
recommend check-in — design only, no vane code; the name and the now-or-horizon timing are Keaton's word, and Ojjo has nothing to measure until Glow runs its first program.
